ostitution, illness, and many other threats to bourgeois society. The statisticians, often trained as jurists, economists and doctors, saw themselves as pioneers of a better future. Offering an original perspective on the tensions between universalism and the rise of the nation-state in the nineteenth century, this book will appeal to historians, statisticians, and social scientists in general.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  aAdolphe Quetelet.  aEuropean nation-states.  aEuropean statistical movement.  aGerman.  aGrand Duchy of Badene.  agovernment statistics.  ainternational statistical congresses.  aliberal polity.  anineteenth century statistics.  aofficial statistics.  ascientific neutrality.  auniversality.1 aRanderaad, Nico, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781526147530zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526147530zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526147530/original  a978-3-11-128363-0 Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA